  "market_context": "Intraday price action on NASDAQ 100 E-mini Futures (NQ1!) during a bullish move toward a higher time frame PD array. The analyst analyzes how price reacts to intermediate bearish order blocks formed after liquidity sweeps and structure breaks.",
  "key_observation": "As price trends upward toward a higher time frame PD array, it repeatedly finds support at intermediate bearish order blocks—each formed by a down-close candle that swept prior liquidity—before continuing higher.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the initial liquidity sweep (low) and subsequent break of structure downward, then locate the up-close candle that swept liquidity before the break, marking its open as a bearish OB.",
    "Step 2: Observe price reacting (finding support) at that bearish OB as it moves higher, confirming its validity as a resistance-turned-support zone.",
    "Step 3: Identify the next down-close candle in the uptrend that swept a new low; treat its body as the next bearish OB and anticipate price support there.",
    "Step 4: Confirm price is supported at the second OB (e.g., around 11805.50), reinforcing the pattern of sequential OB respect en route to the HTF PD array target (e.g., 11963.00).",
    "Step 5: Note the use of mean threshold (0.5 Fib of OB body) instead of full open for tighter stop placement, reducing risk from ~3.5 to ~1.75 points."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "When price moves directionally toward a higher time frame PD array, intermediate order blocks formed during prior liquidity sweeps act as high-probability support/resistance zones. Using mean threshold entries improves R:R without sacrificing validity.",
